attr.attrdef: Current physical state of the trail or trail segment (FGDC Trail Data Standard, 2011).

edom.edomvd: Trail exists, is open to the public, and is physically present and observable.
Trail exists, but is seasonally closed, closed for repairs, or closed due to a hazard. Intent is that the trail will reopen at a later date.
A trail that was no longer needed and has been removed from service. The trail has been permanently closed or altered to return to natural state.

Planned trail identified by an appropriate management decision (e.g. NEPA, Land Management Plan, NHT/NST Comprehensive Management Plan). Also used to describe the trail during the construction phase until it becomes open to the public.
Trail is proposed and no management decision has been made (e.g. NEPA, Land Management Plan, NHT/NST Comprehensive Management Plan).
Trail status is unknown.

attr.attrdef: The predominant surface type the user would expect to encounter on the trail or trail segment (FGDC Trail Data Standard, 2011 and NPS FMSS, 2015).
attr.attrdefs: FGDC Trail Data Standard, 2011; NPS FMSS, 2015

codesetd.codesets: FGDC Trail Data Standard, 2011; NPS FMSS, 2015

attr.attrdef: A category that reflects the predominant trail surface and general mode of travel if accompanied by a trail. A fundamental trail category (USFS, 2011).

edom.edomvd: A trail that has a surface consisting predominantly of the ground and that is designed and managed to accommodate use on that surface (USFS, 2011).
A trail that has a surface consisting predominantly of snow or ice and that is designed and managed to accommodate use on that surface (USFS, 2011).
A trail that has a surface consisting predominantly of water (but may include land-based portages) and that is designed and managed to accommodate use on that surface (USFS, 2011).
Trail type is unknown.

attr.attrdef: The prescribed scale of development for a trail, representing its intended design and management standards (NPS Trails (2100) Asset Business Practice, 2013 and FGDC Trail Data Standard, 2011).
attr.attrdefs: NPS Trails (2100) Asset Business Practice, 2013; FGDC Trail Data Standard, 2011

codesetd.codesets: NPS Trails (2100) Asset Business Practice, 2013; FGDC Trail Data Standard, 2011

edom.edomvd: Represents trails that are primitive or undeveloped. These trails have intermittent tread with minimal to nonexistent structures. Class 1 trails typically provide a natural experience in an undisturbed setting (NPS Trails (2100) Asset Business Practice, 2013).

Represents trails that have had some simple or minor development. These trails have continuous but narrow and rough tread with constructed features limited in size and quantity and are generally developed with native material. Class 2 trails typically provide a natural experience in a mostly undisturbed setting (NPS Trails (2100) Asset Business Practice, 2013).

Represents developed or improved trails. These trails have continuous and obvious tread commonly used with structures that can be imported or natural. Class 3 trails typically provide a natural experience in a largely undisturbed setting (NPS Trails (2100) Asset Business Practice, 2013).

Represents highly developed trails. These trails have wide and relatively smooth tread with frequent and substantial structures. Class 4 trails are rarely present in wilderness areas, and their setting may be modified from its natural appearance (NPS Trails (2100) Asset Business Practice, 2013).

Represents fully developed trails. These trails have wide, firm, stable, and uniform tread with frequent or continuous substantial structures. Class 5 trails are commonly associated with visitor centers or high-use recreation sites, and their setting can be highly modified from its natural appearance (NPS Trails (2100) Asset Business Practice, 2013).
Trail class is unknown.
Trail is not official and does not have a class; trail is a social or animal trail.

attr.attrdef: Mode of travel that is actively managed and appropriate on a trail, based on its design and management. These are allowed uses unless specifically prohibited. Applies to all trails except National Historic Trails that are not managed for recreation trail traffic (FGDC Trail Data Standard, 2011).
The extent of permitted access to the feature geometry and associated attributes.

edom.edomvd: Data access is restricted to Internal NPS Only.
Data access is restricted to Secure Access Only where access to the data itself is restricted by permissions assigned to the user.
Data access is open to the public.

attr.attrdef:
NPS alphabetic code (4-characters) of the NPS organizational unit.
Example: YELL

Full name of the NPS organizational unit.
Example: Yellowstone National Park

An NPS unit that administers the unit identified in UNITCODE. Can additionally be used to identify a network or other single entity that has a pre-established four letter code.
Examples: WEAR; SWAN (I&M Network)

Full name of the NPS organizational unit identified in GROUPCODE.
Examples: Western Arctic Parklands; Southwest Alaska Inventory and Monitoring Network
The alpha code of the NPS Region.

Feature label used for labeling purposes where the park or official name does not meet the need of a particular cartographic product.
Example: Sunset Point Overlook Access

Date the feature was initially created.
Example: 02/17/2015

The person who initially created the feature.
Example: John Smith

Date the feature was last edited.
Example: 02/17/2015

The person who last edited the feature.
Example: John Smith

How the geospatial feature was derived.
Examples: Unknown; Digitized; Autonomous GPS; Differential GPS; Surveyed / Geodetically Derived; Geocoded; COGO; Feature Extraction

Source from which the feature was derived.
Examples: Digitized from NAIP aerial photography; GPS Unit Make/Model: Trimble GeoXH

The date of the source material.
Example: 02/17/2015
An estimate of the measurement error in the horizontal (ASPRS, 2014).

edom.edomvd: Data of unknown origin, spatial accuracy, unknown scale or resolution where a minimum mapping unit or scale of reference cannot be statistically determined (Qualitative accuracy assessment). Examples: Legacy data with little or no spatial attribute information.

Survey-grade mapping with a dual-frequency carrier phase GPS/GNSS receiver used for survey monumentation, vertical assessments, boundary surveys, and SET positions. Often a result of a Real-time Kinematic (RTK), Real-time Network (RTN), Static GNSS surveys or traditional survey methods. Examples: Trimble R10,R8,R6 RTK Systems; Javad Triumph 1,2 RTK Systems; EOS Arrow 200 w/ Real-time Network; Nikon 5 Total Station; Trimble S6 Total Station

Resource-grade mapping with a dual-frequency GPS/GNSS receiver likely combined with a dual-frequency antenna using differential corrections. Some Lidar data. Examples: Trimble GeoXH; EOS Arrow 200; Trimble Pathfinder Office/TerraSync w/ differential correction

Resource-grade mapping with a differential-capable GPS/GNSS receiver using differential corrections. Examples: Trimble GeoXT/Geo7X; EOS Arrow 100; Trimble Pathfinder Office/TerraSync w/ differential correction
Mapping with any GPS/GNSS satellite real-time receiver likely corrected with WAAS. Examples: Garmin handheld w/ WAAS; Trimble Juno handheld; EOS Arrow Lite

Mapping with an autonomous GPS/GNSS or location-based services (LBS) receiver designed for recreational or consumer use. Data that are heads-up digitized from sources such as 1:24,000. Examples: Handheld Cellular Device; GPS Watch

At greater (coarser) than 1:24,000 scale, the National Standard for Spatial Data Accuracy (NSSDA) is 13.9 meters with 95% accuracy (ASPRS, 2005). Examples: Heads up digitizing using an old 1:100000 scale NAD 27 map; GPS collected point under heavy canopy

Map selected; nominal accuracy based on geo-referenced background (imagery or map) data scale; refer to metadata of the specific geo-referenced background data used for a better idea of its spatial accuracy. Any hand-digitized data using background imagery such as from NAIP2015, USDA FSA, or other sources.
